    <segment id="1" parent="20" relname="span">
When you get a chance, find this article in the ACM Digital Library:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="enablement">

Chrusch, M. (2000, September &amp; October). Seven great myths of usability. Interactions, 
13-16.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="14" relname="span">

In this article Marc Chrusch brings up some very interesting areas to consider that are 
actually myths about usability.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="15" relname="span"> These myths are based on mis-education and also misuse 
of terms. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="18" relname="span"> Here are the seven myths.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> Go read the article for more information:</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="17" relname="list">

Myth #1:  Usability only increases development costs and lengthens development 
time.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #2:  The user interface is really just adding good practices to make the application 
appealing</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #3:  Usability is user interface design.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #4:  Usability is really just common sense.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #5:  As long as developers are familar with guidelines, good user interfaces will be 
designed.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #6:  Usability testing is not needed if the development team has been working with 
the users a long time and knows what they want.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="17" relname="list">
Myth #7:  &quot;We&apos;ll handle that in the help/training/documentation.&quot;</segment>
